<div id="content">

																				
    				
                
                
    
    
        	    





		
										

        


    
        
        

        <div id="article-wrapper"
            									                    data-global-auto-refresh-switch="on">
        		
        			<figure>
							<img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2009/12/10/1260445127986/Roast-potatoes-002.jpg" width="460" height="276" alt="Roast potatoes"  />
								  <figcaption>The perfect roast potatoes? Photograph: Tim Hill/Alamy</figcaption>
									</figure>
	
    <div id="article-body-blocks">
	    <p>Mmmm potatoes. How I love you. With your starchy allure, earthy goodness and practical versatility, you are the perfect winter comfort food -  more so when you come encased in a crunchy, golden shell with a fluffy middle still steaming from the oven. </p><p>That is how I would have started this blog a week ago. Today my love is waning a little. They have been golden. They have been crispy. They have been fluffy and steaming. But they have also come in 12 different varieties - and that is a lot of roast potato even for a woman who has spent the last two months cooking on a camping stove dreaming of the moment her new cooker would arrive.</p><p>So why the 12 attempts? Partly because it's only when you are without an oven that you realise how beyond delicious a proper roast dinner is. And partly because no <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/christmas" title="More from guardian.co.uk on Christmas">Christmas</a> table is complete with a piping hot pile of roasties - and we decided it was time to find out which combination of potato variety and method would give you the perfect results without the discussion descending into a "Mine are best!" "No mine!" shouting match. </p><p>A new cooker, three types of potato and four celebrity chef recipes later, I - in fact we, given my boyfriend A's understandable enthusiasm for the potato project - have some findings to present.<br /><br />So here's what we tested. We chose Desiree, King Edwards and Maris Piper potatoes as staple, widely-available varieties likely to turn up in your supermarket / veg box / local shop. Our perfect roast potato recipes came courtesy of Delia, Nigella, Heston and Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall - principally because their methods all differ in terms of oven temperature, boiling time, edge fluffing, and fat.</p><p>All potatoes were all cooked on the same shelf, in the same tray, in what seems to be a fairly even oven. Recipes were pretty much followed to the letter save two omissions from Heston's recipe: I didn't add his suggested garlic and rosemary, given that none of the other potatoes has the benefits of herbage; and I didn't boil the reserved potato peel in muslin as I didn't have any to hand  - I just chucked it in with the spuds to cook. Click on the chef's names below to see their full recipe.</p><h2><a href="http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/nigella-lawson/perfect-roast-potatoes-recipe/index.html">Nigella</a></h2>    <span class="inline">
                <img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2009/12/15/1260887368812/Vicky-Frosts-potato-proje-001.jpg" alt="Vicky Frost's potato project - Nigella" width="220" height="132" />
        </a>        			<span class="caption" style="width: 220px;">
				The potato project - Nigella. Photograph: Vicky Frost
			</span>
            </span>
<p><strong>Oven:</strong> high as it will go<br /><strong>Fat:</strong> goose fat<br /><strong>Parboil:</strong> from cold, then boil for four minutes<br /><strong>Fluff:</strong> a strong shake<br /><strong>Special trick:</strong> sprinkle semolina over pots prior to putting them into the fat for extra crunch</p><h2>Results</h2><p><strong>Faff factor</strong><br />Not bad, although if you have anything else in your oven at the same time as your potatoes, you'll need to watch it doesn't get too hot. The semolina seemed a bit unnecessary - these crisp up well enough in the goosefat to not need extra crunch, and a couple of extra minutes boiling would have given more texture on the outside.</p><p><strong>Potato factor</strong><br />Lovely appearance: a deeper, more inviting gold than others. The crispiest potatoes of the four recipes, but not our favourite for taste. They are also quite heavy. If you've got roasted meat, stuffing, etc it might feel like an indulgence too far - and beyond the goose fat, you have to search for the potato flavour.</p><p><strong>Variety factor</strong><br />Desiree: Fluffy but still firm. Good and crisp. Flavour works well with goose fat<br />King Edward: Super crispy with a good light interior. But taste is more goose than potato.<br />Maris Piper: More hard than crispy, and very heavy inside. Tastes like a chip.</p><p><strong>Verdict</strong><br />A bit heavy inside and don't fluff quite as well as they should outside. Best recipe for King Edwards, good results with Desiree, but not great for Maris Pipers. A bit too rich for us.</p><h2><a href=" http://www.deliaonline.com/recipes/type-of-dish/party-food/accompaniment/perfect-roast-potatoes.html">Delia</a></h2>    <span class="inline wide">
                <img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2009/12/15/1260887089757/Vicky-Frosts-potato-proje-001.jpg" alt="Vicky Frost's potato project - Delia" width="460" height="276" />
        </a>        			<span class="caption" style="width: 460px;">
				The potato project - Delia. Clockwise from top left: Desiree, King Edwards, Maris Piper. Photograph: Vicky Frost
			</span>
            </span>
<p><strong>Oven:</strong> 220&deg;C<br /><strong>Fat:</strong> dripping or lard (I'd just roasted a chicken so they went in that roasting tray with a bit of lard added.)<br /><strong>Parboil:</strong> into boiling water for 10 minutes<br /><strong>Fluff:</strong> a strong shake<br /><strong>Special tip:</strong> use a skewer to check the outsides are cooked enough to fluff. (Delia really does love skewers).</p><h2>Results</h2><p><strong>Faff factor</strong><br />The least faffy of the four, as you might expect. Delia has you put the oven tray of hot fat onto the heat as you baste the potatoes, which seals them well. (Everyone else might already do this, but I haven't before. I think it makes a difference). She says this means you don't need to turn them. I would recommend ignoring that and giving them a shake halfway through</p><p><strong>Potato factor</strong><br />Good potatoes, but we found them a little less golden than might be desired, and a bit greasier than the ideal roastie. But in terms of fluffy outsides and in: 10 minutes parboiling might be optimum before shaking – fluffy enough so they pick up all the fat (see Nigella), but not so they fall apart (Heston) </p><p><strong>Variety factor</strong><br />Desiree: Delia's favourite for her roasties, and A agreed with her. My problem? A Desiree stays just a little bit too firm for me. I want more fluff inside<br />King Edward: Not a complete disaster, but almost. The insides were too<br />floury and the potatoes seemed to have absorbed a lot of the oil<br />flavour – and not in a great way.<br />Maris Piper: These however, made up for the Edwards: the perfect crisp, with a lovely crunch collapsing into fluffy, creamy insides. Tastes like a roast potato, with good balance of oil vs pots.</p><p><strong>Verdict</strong><br />A bit patchy. And neither of us were overkeen on the lard, even though we didn't use much of it. But the Maris Pipers were a treat.</p><h2><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/food/recipes/database/perfectroastpotatoes_13801.shtml">Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall</a></h2>    <span class="inline">
                <img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2009/12/15/1260887702166/Vicky-Frosts-potato-proje-001.jpg" alt="Vicky Frost's potato project - Hugh" width="220" height="132" />
        </a>        			<span class="caption" style="width: 220px;">
				The potato project - Hugh. Photograph: Vicky Frost
			</span>
            </span>
<p><strong>Oven:</strong> same heat as your roast (sensible Hugh!)<br /><strong>Fat:</strong> from your roast but only if there's plenty of it. There wasn't so we used groundnut oil, as advised by HFW, with some duck fat added Parboil: into boiling water for eight minutes<br /><strong>Fluff:</strong> cool completely and then use a fork to roughen the edges<br /><strong>Special trick:</strong> a recipe written for people making other things at the same time – also pointers on whether you keep them in when you turn up the oven for the yorkshires, etc.</p><h2>Results</h2><p><strong>Faff factor</strong><br />Not bad. A bit annoying to have to cool the potatoes before they go back in the oven, and roughing the skin with a  fork seems a bit unneccesary – giving them a good shake would probably give the same kind of results.</p><p><strong>Potato factor</strong><br />Seemed like a large amount of oil (½ cm in the tin), but they crisped up wonderfully and were the least greasy of the four. Groundnut oil sounded extremely unpromising – but in fact gave a brilliant potato, as well as being healthier to boot. However, they do need a bit longer than HFW suggests: an extra 10 minutes makes the difference.</p><p><strong>Variety factor</strong><br />Desiree: A potato that tastes of potato. Delicious! Creamy inside, decent crunch on the outside. Looks good and holds its shape. A potato to draw admiring glances.<br />King Edward: Hugh recommends Edwards. Not quite sure why, as they performed the least well; the outsides fabulously crispy, but the insides very soggy – almost mash like.<br />Maris Piper: Seemed to appreciate the fork method over pan-shaking method, you could hear the crunch practically next door when we broke into them. The insides proved creamy and sweet and tasting of Maris rather than animal fat. A champion potato.</p><p><strong>Verdict</strong><br />Surprisingly fantastic. A practical suggestion to switch to groundnut oil that really pays off: much lighter potatoes, and with more of a potato taste to boot. Ditch the animal fat Would be brilliant with gravy.</p><h2><a href="http://www.potatolovers.co.uk/content/recipes/info/?id=70">Heston</a></h2>    <span class="inline">
                <img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2009/12/15/1260889322956/Vicky-Frosts-potato-proje-001.jpg" alt="Vicky Frost's potato project - Heston" width="220" height="132" />
        </a>        			<span class="caption" style="width: 220px;">
				The potato project - Heston. Photograph: Vicky Frost
			</span>
            </span>
<p><strong>Oven:</strong> 190&deg;C<br /><strong>Fat:</strong> Olive oil<br /><strong>Parboil:</strong> 20 minutes. 20 minutes!<br /><strong>Fluff:</strong> a gentle shake<br /><strong>Special trick:</strong> Boil your potato peelings up with your potatoes for added flavour (in muslin, Heston recommends, but I ignored to no detriment).</p><h2>Results</h2><p><strong>Faff factor</strong><br />Yes, this was faffy. Keep the potato peelings, then put all the potatoes under cold running water for three minutes, then wrap the peelings in muslin and into the pan, then try and keep the potatoes in one piece in the roasting tray after such a long boil. I did curse Heston more than once.</p><p><strong>Potato factor</strong><br />More oil than HFW, and more expensive oil I might add. I wasn't keen on the olive oil flavour of the finished roasties – but A was very impressed. Also, either the peelings really do make the potatoes taste like potatoes x2, or the fact Heston had me using more salt than I'd usually use – or a combination of both – made these super-delicious.</p><p><strong>Variety factor</strong><br />Desiree: Fairly Crispy, with a rather dense inside – but a good colour and shape given that they'd been boiled for so long. And lovely flavour. Really earthy and delicious.<br />King Edward: Ah. Finding the point that Edwards go from soft and fluffy to complete collapse is quite difficult – I lost half the pan of this variety to the sink when I tried to drain them. Of the ones in the oven: crisp outside but really quite soggy within. Cracking taste though.<br />Maris Piper: Fairly crispy, fairly fluffy. Fairly boring? Not at all – amazingly tasty. Had to remove the plate from my reach in order to stop eating them, and they were the last potato we tested. </p><p><strong>Verdict</strong><br />A bit odd. Texture is very underwhelming and quite heavy, but the taste really is delicious – or it is if you don't find so much olive oil a bit offputting on a roastie destined for a British table. More enthusiastic response from A, however.</p><h2>The final verdict</h2><p>Oddly, given that it's Nigella who normally gets the nod from me I'd combine Delia's parboiling and shaking, HFW's groundnut oil, Heston's seasoning and potato peeling trick. Do that to a Maris Piper for me, and a Desiree for A, and we would be truly happy.</p>
    </div>

		
            	    





		
										

        


        </div>

    
    
                
</div>

		
