			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7254196">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/kendrew" title="User profile page">kendrew</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">17 December 2009 2:02PM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Don't overcomplicate a simple culinary task; start with spuds that you have grown yourself. Kind Edward is a good choice, or Desiree. Peel par boil and drain. Shake the pan to fluff the edges and place in roasting tray with pre heated goose/duck/ chicken fat.
</p><p>Ground nut oil is a good second choice, olive oil less so. Bang in a pre heated very hot oven. There is some advantage to removing the tray when the spuds are crisp and golden; leave the spuds to cool then slam them back in for a further 5 minutes and serve immediately.
</p><p>Nigellas semolina is an ingredient too far; some woody rosemary or thyme is a nice addtion to the tray about 15 minutes before removing from the oven.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
