                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/discussion/avatars/2010/08/23/HoistThatRag/e5e3a8d7-670f-4775-aef7-480c9468a8bb/60x60.png" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/HoistThatRag" title="User profile page">HoistThatRag</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">17 December 2009 2:27PM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>This is the kind of taste test I like!
</p><p>I saw Jamie Oliver's version on the telly with the "potato masher trick" - looked like a good idea. Cook the potatoes as one of the many recipes above, bang them in the oven.. then halfway through cooking, just flatten the potatoes with a potato masher, bang them back in the oven. Hardly rocket science.. great idea though, and I'm going to give it a try this year.
</p><p>Last year we used a Nigella idea - I think it has a similar effect to Jamie Oliver's - cut the potatoes <i>on the diagonal</i>, rather than straight down the middle - it increases surface area so more to crisp up. They were bloomin marvellous. Hmm.. maybe it is rocket science?
</p><p>And another Nigella recommendation - roast parsnips.. but with maple syrup drizzled over it. I'm dead on Xmas day if I don't cook those - my wife loves them!</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
